Dialogue: 0,0:00:20.24,0:00:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,Hello. Um, I had the wrong announcements\Non the table this morning.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:26.40,0:00:32.07,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the rest of the announcements are\Num we must leave promptly at five
Dialogue: 0,0:00:32.07,0:00:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,o'clock. So, um there's another event\Nhere at 7 tonight. Little Women, they're
Dialogue: 0,0:00:37.44,0:00:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,putting on the play Little Women. Um and\Nso, uh we will have to leave promptly by
Dialogue: 0,0:00:42.96,0:00:47.12,Default,,0,0,0,,5:00. Uh make sure that you clean up\Naround your seats if you can because
Dialogue: 0,0:00:47.12,0:00:50.96,Default,,0,0,0,,there is another event and if we can\Nhelp them by cleaning up that would help
Dialogue: 0,0:00:50.96,0:00:57.84,Default,,0,0,0,,tremendously. Um, there are pre-orders\Nfor today's lecture in the bookstore.
Dialogue: 0,0:00:57.84,0:01:01.92,Default,,0,0,0,,So, if you'd like to fill one out, we\Nwill definitely mail you one as soon as
Dialogue: 0,0:01:01.92,0:01:08.47,Default,,0,0,0,,they come out. And, um, the schedule for\N2010 is also at the bookstore. So, if
Dialogue: 0,0:01:08.47,0:01:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,you want to pick those up. And, um, let\Nme see. I think that's it.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:14.72,0:01:21.84,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Good.\N>> Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:21.84,0:01:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay. In the um b birth process, I\Nforgot to mention
Dialogue: 0,0:01:28.08,0:01:39.11,Default,,0,0,0,,uh I I was born addicted to nicotine.\NThat's a fact.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.11,0:01:44.15,Default,,0,0,0,,I was born addicted to nicotine\Nbecause
Dialogue: 0,0:01:44.15,0:01:49.28,Default,,0,0,0,,when I was a\Nwouldbe infant
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.28,0:01:55.68,Default,,0,0,0,,uh women everybody smoked and uh\Npresident smoked every everybody smoked.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.68,0:02:05.20,Default,,0,0,0,,It was uh uh the result of a certain uh\Nera in
Dialogue: 0,0:02:05.20,0:02:10.80,Default,,0,0,0,,American development\Nand everybody smoked in that age and so
Dialogue: 0,0:02:10.80,0:02:17.59,Default,,0,0,0,,my mother smoked too. She was a flapper\Nand she was modern and she smoked. So
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.59,0:02:21.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the women didn't think anything of that\Nbecause smoke only goes down to here and
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.28,0:02:27.28,Default,,0,0,0,,the baby's down here. So what's the\Nproblem?
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.28,0:02:38.64,Default,,0,0,0,,So when I was born, the first thing I\Nwanted was anybody got a smoke.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:38.64,0:02:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay,\Nthat's a fact. Resist. That's a fact.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:46.72,0:02:52.72,Default,,0,0,0,,You can be born addicted to nicotine\Nbefore you have your first smoke. So as
Dialogue: 0,0:02:52.72,0:02:59.12,Default,,0,0,0,,soon I was born, there was all these\Nloud noises and bright lights and I
Dialogue: 0,0:02:59.12,0:03:08.87,Default,,0,0,0,,needed a smoke.\NSo these make up the vicissitudes of
Dialogue: 0,0:03:08.87,0:03:14.87,Default,,0,0,0,,life. You see in in those days everybody\Nsmoked and my my family were all
Dialogue: 0,0:03:14.87,0:03:18.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Victorians.\NMy grandparents were all Victorians. In
Dialogue: 0,0:03:18.80,0:03:24.08,Default,,0,0,0,,the Victorian era, everybody smoked all\Nthe time, everywhere, except my two
Dialogue: 0,0:03:24.08,0:03:29.04,Default,,0,0,0,,grandmothers. Old grandmothers could get\Naway with not smoking.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.04,0:03:33.12,Default,,0,0,0,,But I had one grandmother who was more\Nmodern, and she said, "I'll have a
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.12,0:03:40.00,Default,,0,0,0,,cigarette with you to be sociable."\NAnd they all lived to be 95 or so, so I
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.00,0:03:46.15,Default,,0,0,0,,guess cigarettes weren't all that bad in\Nthose days.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:46.15,0:03:54.31,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. So, where were we now?\NUh what's slide? Okay.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.31,0:03:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh all right. So all of these things\Ncould make a lecture. Any one of these
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.36,0:04:04.72,Default,,0,0,0,,things that we talk about\Nuh obviously your vocation and your
Dialogue: 0,0:04:04.72,0:04:09.92,Default,,0,0,0,,courtship.\NUh the quality of marriage, the quality
Dialogue: 0,0:04:09.92,0:04:14.15,Default,,0,0,0,,of marriage. If you see yourself as\Npartners, if you see yourself as
Dialogue: 0,0:04:14.15,0:04:19.60,Default,,0,0,0,,mutually beneficial,\Nyou're committed to the partnership. And
Dialogue: 0,0:04:19.60,0:04:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,uh if you're lucky, you find a good wife\Nand uh a good husband. And if you're not
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.56,0:04:38.16,Default,,0,0,0,,so lucky, your life is hell,\Nmurder, and suicide. Other than that,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:38.16,0:04:43.04,Default,,0,0,0,,we looked at all the factors that\Ninfluence success.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.04,0:04:46.80,Default,,0,0,0,,Um,\Nbelief in yourself, to believe in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:46.80,0:04:50.08,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself.\NUh, it's important to believe in
Dialogue: 0,0:04:50.08,0:04:55.36,Default,,0,0,0,,yourself. No matter where you are in\Nlife,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.36,0:04:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,want you to have a positive attitude\Ntowards that.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:59.36,0:05:04.63,Default,,0,0,0,,Let's say you've done everything wrong\Nand you're in jail and you're being sued
Dialogue: 0,0:05:04.63,0:05:10.56,Default,,0,0,0,,by everybody and everybody's left you.\NYou're a great success
Dialogue: 0,0:05:10.56,0:05:19.91,Default,,0,0,0,,cuz you have now learned what does not\Nwork in this world.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:19.91,0:05:25.19,Default,,0,0,0,,However, there are some people\Ncongenally unable to learn what does not
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.19,0:05:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,work in this world.\NWe have a friend of ours who who
Dialogue: 0,0:05:29.52,0:05:35.36,Default,,0,0,0,,examines people that are chronically in\Nand out of prison in the in the in the
Dialogue: 0,0:05:35.36,0:05:42.16,Default,,0,0,0,,prognosis and uh there are people that\Njust never get it congenatively
Dialogue: 0,0:05:42.16,0:05:46.72,Default,,0,0,0,,just don't have the capacity or the\Ninterest or
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.72,0:05:54.08,Default,,0,0,0,,uh unable to learn from experience.\NSo we're happy that if we have a bad
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.08,0:05:59.60,Default,,0,0,0,,experience, at least the average person\Nlearns that we don't want to go that
Dialogue: 0,0:05:59.60,0:06:03.84,Default,,0,0,0,,way.\NWe're the average person learns. That
Dialogue: 0,0:06:03.84,0:06:08.80,Default,,0,0,0,,way does not work. But there are some\Npeople that are inherently incapable of
Dialogue: 0,0:06:08.80,0:06:13.19,Default,,0,0,0,,learning from experience.\NWhat did we say? They were 6% of the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:13.19,0:06:17.60,Default,,0,0,0,,population at one time. Let's see if\Nthat's still correct. There are people
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.60,0:06:24.63,Default,,0,0,0,,unable to learn from experience and it\Ncomprise about 6% of the population 7%
Dialogue: 0,0:06:24.63,0:06:29.68,Default,,0,0,0,,6%\N6% of the population is unable
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.68,0:06:33.28,Default,,0,0,0,,congenitally\Nuh
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.28,0:06:39.36,Default,,0,0,0,,unable to learn from experience.\NAnd you see the receivist criminal does
Dialogue: 0,0:06:39.36,0:06:43.60,Default,,0,0,0,,this. He lands in jail. He goes out and\Nthe first thing he does is what put him
Dialogue: 0,0:06:43.60,0:06:49.84,Default,,0,0,0,,just in jail before.\NWe used to have sexual offenders
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.84,0:06:55.60,Default,,0,0,0,,uh that went after children and the\Nminute they let them out, what's the
Dialogue: 0,0:06:55.60,0:06:58.96,Default,,0,0,0,,first thing they did? They went to the\Npark and began to sexually molest
Dialogue: 0,0:06:58.96,0:07:03.52,Default,,0,0,0,,children. In less than five minutes\Nletting them out, they're already in the
Dialogue: 0,0:07:03.52,0:07:07.84,Default,,0,0,0,,park soliciting some child. And you say,\N"Didn't they learn anything from
Dialogue: 0,0:07:07.84,0:07:15.19,Default,,0,0,0,,experience?" And the answer was no.\NThey apparently lack the capacity.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:15.19,0:07:20.63,Default,,0,0,0,,So instead of condemning them, we should\Nbe compassionate but also take proper
Dialogue: 0,0:07:20.63,0:07:26.16,Default,,0,0,0,,protection. This person is nice as they\Ncan be and they can be quite amiable and
Dialogue: 0,0:07:26.16,0:07:33.36,Default,,0,0,0,,pleasant. Uh is unable to learn from\Nexperience. So all we can do is use bars
Dialogue: 0,0:07:33.36,0:07:39.84,Default,,0,0,0,,or whatever to prevent them uh from\Nmolesting children in the park.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.84,0:07:44.40,Default,,0,0,0,,the adverse events and success, family,\Nworld conditions,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:44.40,0:07:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,uh, world conditions, uh, affect us more\Nthan we think. We say, well, that's on
Dialogue: 0,0:07:50.00,0:07:55.68,Default,,0,0,0,,the other side of the world. But don't\Nforget the human consciousness is
Dialogue: 0,0:07:55.68,0:08:01.12,Default,,0,0,0,,collective. There's a collective human\Nconsciousness. So when you see something
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.12,0:08:06.31,Default,,0,0,0,,on the other side of the world without\Nyour being aware of it, it's affecting
Dialogue: 0,0:08:06.31,0:08:13.12,Default,,0,0,0,,you. Okay? Uh, that's a fact. Resist.\NThat's a fact. The things that you think
Dialogue: 0,0:08:13.12,0:08:17.28,Default,,0,0,0,,have nothing to do with you, that's on\Nthe other side of the world. Different
Dialogue: 0,0:08:17.28,0:08:22.72,Default,,0,0,0,,country, different culture. That's got\Nno effect on me. It affects the
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.72,0:08:28.40,Default,,0,0,0,,collective consciousness of mankind to\Nwhich you are connected. Okay? Everyone
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.40,0:08:32.80,Default,,0,0,0,,is connected to the collective\Nconsciousness of mankind. Therefore,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.80,0:08:37.68,Default,,0,0,0,,everyone is influenced by world events\Nwhether they know it or not. resist.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:37.68,0:08:40.47,Default,,0,0,0,,That's a good thing to know. You say,\N"Well, that's got nothing to do with
Dialogue: 0,0:08:40.47,0:08:45.04,Default,,0,0,0,,me." That's those nut jobs on the other\Nside of the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.04,0:08:49.68,Default,,0,0,0,,It does affect you. It affects your\Nsense of inner security, uh your trust
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.68,0:08:55.20,Default,,0,0,0,,to your fellow human beings and your\Noverall worldview. Uh whether it's of
Dialogue: 0,0:08:55.20,0:09:01.76,Default,,0,0,0,,the pessimistic or optimistic,\Nuh mankind evolves slowly and often by
Dialogue: 0,0:09:01.76,0:09:06.24,Default,,0,0,0,,leaps and jumps. Nothing will happen for\Na couple hundred years and suddenly you
Dialogue: 0,0:09:06.24,0:09:11.51,Default,,0,0,0,,see an enormous jump.\NAll right. World conditions then our
Dialogue: 0,0:09:11.51,0:09:16.48,Default,,0,0,0,,health affects our uh our mental\Ncondition and our mental condition
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.48,0:09:20.95,Default,,0,0,0,,affects our health. The poorer our\Nmental condition the more likelihood is
Dialogue: 0,0:09:20.95,0:09:27.68,Default,,0,0,0,,that we'll have health problems. Uh on\Nthe other hand, a lot of illnesses seem
Dialogue: 0,0:09:27.68,0:09:35.27,Default,,0,0,0,,to be uh genetic and uh we recently did\Na published a book called um health and
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.27,0:09:39.83,Default,,0,0,0,,healing. Was that it? Health and\Nhealing. Is that the name of it?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:39.83,0:09:41.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Healing and recovery.\N>> Huh?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:41.83,0:09:45.27,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Healing and recovery.\N>> What's the name of it?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:45.27,0:09:47.83,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Our book.\N>> The one on health and healing. Is that
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.83,0:09:49.83,Default,,0,0,0,,what's the name of the book?\N>> Healing and recovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:49.83,0:09:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,>> Healing and recovery.\Nwho recently published a book which is a
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.72,0:10:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,very good one\Ncalled healing and recovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:04.39,0:10:09.20,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh I in I include a lot of personal\Nexperiences in there myself
Dialogue: 0,0:10:09.20,0:10:15.27,Default,,0,0,0,,and uh learned a lot of things about the\Nhealth system in general specific health
Dialogue: 0,0:10:15.27,0:10:20.56,Default,,0,0,0,,problems in particular and certain\Ndoctors etc.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:20.56,0:10:26.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I would always use the arm on any doctor\Nyou're seeing. You see, and uh doctors
Dialogue: 0,0:10:26.95,0:10:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,seem to have lost a certain sense of\Ncaringness that was endemic in the
Dialogue: 0,0:10:31.44,0:10:35.68,Default,,0,0,0,,profession. When I went through medical\Nschool and of course I went to a Jesuit
Dialogue: 0,0:10:35.68,0:10:43.83,Default,,0,0,0,,university and um caringness about the\Npatient uh was extremely important. And
Dialogue: 0,0:10:43.83,0:10:47.68,Default,,0,0,0,,when I had a very big clinic, we found\Nthat
Dialogue: 0,0:10:47.68,0:10:52.95,Default,,0,0,0,,uh the doctors, we had a lot of doctors\Non the staff and certain doctors had
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.95,0:10:58.39,Default,,0,0,0,,very high recovery rates and other\Ndoctors had very low recovery rates. And
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.39,0:11:03.60,Default,,0,0,0,,we discovered that the doctors who had\Nhigh recovery rates uh cared about their
Dialogue: 0,0:11:03.60,0:11:08.72,Default,,0,0,0,,patients. They cared about them. Doesn't\Nmean they have a positive counter
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.72,0:11:13.76,Default,,0,0,0,,transference. It just means that as\Nhuman beings they care. They care
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.76,0:11:18.32,Default,,0,0,0,,whether you get well. They care whether\Nyou are happy. They care whether you've
Dialogue: 0,0:11:18.32,0:11:24.24,Default,,0,0,0,,stopped suffering. So to have a caring\Ndoctor is extremely important. So you
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.24,0:11:31.92,Default,,0,0,0,,could use your arm, use the arm and\Ncheck out your doctor.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:31.92,0:11:37.83,Default,,0,0,0,,He's a caring doctor and therefore a\Ngood doctor to see.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:37.83,0:11:45.27,Default,,0,0,0,,Some people some people had huge uh uh\Npractices and did extraordinarily well.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:45.27,0:11:50.07,Default,,0,0,0,,And other people had a little small\Npractices and did orally. And it was the
Dialogue: 0,0:11:50.07,0:11:56.72,Default,,0,0,0,,whole difference was caring.\NCaring. when you care. So, the same
Dialogue: 0,0:11:56.72,0:12:02.95,Default,,0,0,0,,thing applies to uh all of your life. To\Ncare about your neighbors, to care about
Dialogue: 0,0:12:02.95,0:12:08.80,Default,,0,0,0,,your pets, to care about how your lawn\Nlooks, to care about yourself, that you
Dialogue: 0,0:12:08.80,0:12:13.36,Default,,0,0,0,,look halfway decent when you go out,\Nthat you're not too ugly and don't scare
Dialogue: 0,0:12:13.36,0:12:18.56,Default,,0,0,0,,people.\NThere's a point at which you should get
Dialogue: 0,0:12:18.56,0:12:31.44,Default,,0,0,0,,a face job. You know, I mean, just\Nkindness for your fellow human beings.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.44,0:12:37.51,Default,,0,0,0,,to care about life because the essence\Nof life uh the essence of all life is
Dialogue: 0,0:12:37.51,0:12:42.39,Default,,0,0,0,,divinity.\NAll of life is the expression of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:42.39,0:12:46.48,Default,,0,0,0,,divinity.\NAll of life is an expression of
Dialogue: 0,0:12:46.48,0:12:52.00,Default,,0,0,0,,divinity. Resist all of life is God.\NResist.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.00,0:12:57.12,Default,,0,0,0,,All of life is God. So you're caring\Nthis about your garden. You're caring
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.12,0:13:00.95,Default,,0,0,0,,this about your kidneys. You're carrying\Nthis about the dogs. Right now the
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.95,0:13:06.16,Default,,0,0,0,,hummingbirds are back. I hope you have\Nhummingbird food up. I hear them out
Dialogue: 0,0:13:06.16,0:13:15.51,Default,,0,0,0,,there. They go\Nlittle hummingbirds. They're so cute.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.51,0:13:21.92,Default,,0,0,0,,Don't shoot the hummingbirds. No.\NI'm sure there's hummingbird killers out
Dialogue: 0,0:13:21.92,0:13:25.92,Default,,0,0,0,,there someplace.\NAnything that lives, you'll find
Dialogue: 0,0:13:25.92,0:13:30.24,Default,,0,0,0,,somebody that wants to stalk them and\Nshoot them.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.24,0:13:35.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Yeah.\NI've never been a I've never been much
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.60,0:13:39.76,Default,,0,0,0,,on hunting.\NAnd uh my father wasn't big on hunting
Dialogue: 0,0:13:39.76,0:13:44.88,Default,,0,0,0,,either. He got taken to go hunting\Nbecause all men in Wisconsin in the fall
Dialogue: 0,0:13:44.88,0:13:48.24,Default,,0,0,0,,went hunting.\NSo to be a good guy, he went along with
Dialogue: 0,0:13:48.24,0:13:52.63,Default,,0,0,0,,the hunting and he finally got a deer in\Nthe sights and he got and he started to
Dialogue: 0,0:13:52.63,0:13:59.76,Default,,0,0,0,,shake. He looked at the deer and it's\Nlife energy
Dialogue: 0,0:13:59.76,0:14:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,almost knocked them out and he realized\Nthat he could not pull the trigger. So
Dialogue: 0,0:14:04.39,0:14:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,he never went deer hunting again.\NA
Dialogue: 0,0:14:10.00,0:14:16.00,Default,,0,0,0,,deer fever. You look down the telescopic\Nsites and you see this incredible,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.00,0:14:19.68,Default,,0,0,0,,incredible creature.\NAnd we have a little place where we go
Dialogue: 0,0:14:19.68,0:14:24.32,Default,,0,0,0,,in the summertime. And these incredible\Ncreatures with their little funny ears
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.32,0:14:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,sit out there and the idea of killing\NBambi is just not even conceivable.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:31.60,0:14:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,How can you kill Bambi? Right.\NHow can you kill Bambi?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.44,0:14:44.24,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. That's how your world\Nconditions affect us. Our wealth, our
Dialogue: 0,0:14:44.24,0:14:50.80,Default,,0,0,0,,health, our financial comfort zone.\NComfort zone is simple. Just to spend
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.80,0:14:57.51,Default,,0,0,0,,less than what you make. That's simple.\NSimple concept.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:57.51,0:15:02.00,Default,,0,0,0,,Nobody lives by it. That's how we have\Ncharge cards, right? So today, what you
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.00,0:15:05.60,Default,,0,0,0,,figure is how much you can afford to pay\Na month on your charge card. And that
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.60,0:15:10.24,Default,,0,0,0,,decides on your level of living. Aging\Nof course you're going to go through all
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.24,0:15:15.68,Default,,0,0,0,,different phenomena. Aging has a\Nprofound effect. Uh the 80s certainly
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.68,0:15:21.51,Default,,0,0,0,,are not the 60s and certainly not the\N40s and certainly not the 30s. So we
Dialogue: 0,0:15:21.51,0:15:26.56,Default,,0,0,0,,take into account and many things I say\Nto myself. Well, it's because of how
Dialogue: 0,0:15:26.56,0:15:32.24,Default,,0,0,0,,long I've lived that I see it that way.\NOkay, it's not really political. It's
Dialogue: 0,0:15:32.24,0:15:37.36,Default,,0,0,0,,not really intellectual. It's just that\NI belong to a different age group.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:37.36,0:15:40.63,Default,,0,0,0,,My age group lived through certain\Nthings that people in different age
Dialogue: 0,0:15:40.63,0:15:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,groups did not live through\Nbecause I didn't live through it. Their
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.39,0:15:49.75,Default,,0,0,0,,understanding of it is different than\Nmine.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.75,0:15:55.51,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh our philosophical position\Nuh some people are intellectuals and
Dialogue: 0,0:15:55.51,0:16:01.51,Default,,0,0,0,,calibrate in the 400s and they eat up\Nphilosophy and they love to read books.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:01.51,0:16:07.19,Default,,0,0,0,,I used to read 500 books a year, 500\Nbooks a year for decades. And I made
Dialogue: 0,0:16:07.19,0:16:14.32,Default,,0,0,0,,notes on each book and kept them all on\Nfile. Uh 500 books a year. So how many
Dialogue: 0,0:16:14.32,0:16:18.48,Default,,0,0,0,,books a year do you read? Depends on how\Nmuch time you've got and how much
Dialogue: 0,0:16:18.48,0:16:22.95,Default,,0,0,0,,intellectual curiosity.\NBut I found philosophic works of the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:22.95,0:16:27.44,Default,,0,0,0,,great books of the western world for\Ninstance. I I forgot the name of the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:27.44,0:16:33.44,Default,,0,0,0,,university. It's out west of California\Nthat the whole curriculum is the what's
Dialogue: 0,0:16:33.44,0:16:36.39,Default,,0,0,0,,the name of it?\NThomas
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.39,0:16:40.88,Default,,0,0,0,,>> St. John\N>> Thomas Aquinas
Dialogue: 0,0:16:40.88,0:16:46.39,Default,,0,0,0,,>> John\N>> St. John that's right St. John, uh, the
Dialogue: 0,0:16:46.39,0:16:50.63,Default,,0,0,0,,whole curriculum is the great books of\Nthe Western world. That's really quite
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.63,0:16:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,profound, isn't it? Quite profound that\Nthey make a whole curriculum of it. That
Dialogue: 0,0:16:55.12,0:17:00.39,Default,,0,0,0,,would be a great place to go or send\Nsomebody. And uh, I'd like to go again.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:00.39,0:17:04.95,Default,,0,0,0,,I don't have enough time.\NI'm sure if I went back to the
Dialogue: 0,0:17:04.95,0:17:09.12,Default,,0,0,0,,university now, I'd just be fascinated.\NAll the stuff I missed the first time
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.12,0:17:13.91,Default,,0,0,0,,through, the stuff I've forgotten, I\Nsay, "Oh my god, I forgot that Deart
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.91,0:17:17.52,Default,,0,0,0,,said that." Whatever.\NAll right.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:17.52,0:17:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Introvert versus extrovert. Did we find\Nour comfort zone to be within ourself or
Dialogue: 0,0:17:24.79,0:17:31.84,Default,,0,0,0,,only when we're other with other people?\NUh be to be an ambbervert would be
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.84,0:17:36.55,Default,,0,0,0,,perfect. It's okay if you're alone all\Nby yourself and it's okay if you're
Dialogue: 0,0:17:36.55,0:17:41.28,Default,,0,0,0,,surrounded by people. Your physical\Nappearance of course has an effect on
Dialogue: 0,0:17:41.28,0:17:44.16,Default,,0,0,0,,people both consciously and\Nunconsciously.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:44.16,0:17:50.00,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're just badl looking, you got to\Nlearn to live with it.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:50.00,0:17:54.32,Default,,0,0,0,,If you're irresistible, you got to fight\Noff the women. They're all after your
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.32,0:18:02.88,Default,,0,0,0,,little body.\NI think that's hysterically funny. Okay,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:02.88,0:18:08.00,Default,,0,0,0,,the next one.\NOh, what's the next slide?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.00,0:18:11.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Is there anything uh we need to go back\Nto? Well, we'll have a question and
Dialogue: 0,0:18:11.44,0:18:15.20,Default,,0,0,0,,answer later, but if anybody has a\Nreally pressing question that they want
Dialogue: 0,0:18:15.20,0:18:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,to ask, uh, it's okay with me if you\Nhold up your hand and holler.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:20.96,0:18:26.00,Default,,0,0,0,,It's okay with me if you ask a question.\NUhhuh.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:26.00,0:18:30.08,Default,,0,0,0,,So, the each level of consciousness, as\Nyou can see from what we said this
Dialogue: 0,0:18:30.08,0:18:37.12,Default,,0,0,0,,morning, has its own level of reality.\NReality is therefore a subjective mental
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.12,0:18:42.72,Default,,0,0,0,,presumption\Nand it's both linear and nonlinear
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.72,0:18:47.36,Default,,0,0,0,,and reality is one thing. Truth is what\Nyou say about it.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:47.36,0:18:53.84,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore you finally after many years\Nof meditation and study you come up with
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.84,0:18:58.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the question\Nis is what I consider to be myself or me
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.88,0:19:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,or I real?\NIt's experiential, but is it a reality
Dialogue: 0,0:19:06.32,0:19:12.79,Default,,0,0,0,,or is it the product of mentalization?\NIs there a a real eye? And if what is
Dialogue: 0,0:19:12.79,0:19:16.64,Default,,0,0,0,,the eye?\NBecause we change your education, you're
Dialogue: 0,0:19:16.64,0:19:20.48,Default,,0,0,0,,still me. You take off one leg, you're\Nstill me.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:20.48,0:19:23.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody leaves, you're all by\Nyourself, you're still me. No matter
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.67,0:19:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,what happens, you seem to be stuck with\Nsomething that you call I.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.52,0:19:36.00,Default,,0,0,0,,What is this that you call I?\NIs it an independent entity? How does it
Dialogue: 0,0:19:36.00,0:19:40.40,Default,,0,0,0,,arise?\NSo in the end when looking for
Dialogue: 0,0:19:40.40,0:19:45.36,Default,,0,0,0,,enlightenment,\Nyou begin to examine what is it that I
Dialogue: 0,0:19:45.36,0:19:53.36,Default,,0,0,0,,consider to be myself, my reality.\NWhat hap what is I? Is reality a
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.36,0:19:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,subjective mental presumption?\NUh is it real or not real?
Dialogue: 0,0:19:59.36,0:20:06.32,Default,,0,0,0,,Is reality a truth? Is it the me that's\Nreal? Who or what is the I?
Dialogue: 0,0:20:06.32,0:20:10.00,Default,,0,0,0,,You could say, well, I is the\Nexperiencer.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:10.00,0:20:15.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Therefore, I think the most common one\Nis I am the experiencer.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.76,0:20:19.67,Default,,0,0,0,,At different levels, people will say,\Nwell, I am the that which makes
Dialogue: 0,0:20:19.67,0:20:26.40,Default,,0,0,0,,decisions. I am that which remembers. I\Nam that which imagines things. I am that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:26.40,0:20:32.48,Default,,0,0,0,,which is happy or not happy.\NSo the sense of eye then becomes vague
Dialogue: 0,0:20:32.48,0:20:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,and diffuse and can cover almost\Nanything
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.03,0:20:43.44,Default,,0,0,0,,with u meditation. One of the greatest\Nbenefits of meditation is that which you
Dialogue: 0,0:20:43.44,0:20:50.32,Default,,0,0,0,,choose to call I becomes progressively\Nmore clear and then finally dissolves
Dialogue: 0,0:20:50.32,0:20:54.48,Default,,0,0,0,,altogether\Nand there the only reality that that
Dialogue: 0,0:20:54.48,0:21:01.44,Default,,0,0,0,,remains is the existence of divinity.\NSo I as the experiencer, I'm the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:01.44,0:21:07.28,Default,,0,0,0,,experiencer of my experiencer.\NI you can define as the one who makes
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.28,0:21:13.44,Default,,0,0,0,,decisions. That's what we put in jail is\Nthe eye that made a bad decision.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.44,0:21:19.03,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh we say I is the source of our\Nwillpower.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:19.03,0:21:25.03,Default,,0,0,0,,We say that I is a certain social\Npersonhood. What the world calls I is
Dialogue: 0,0:21:25.03,0:21:31.52,Default,,0,0,0,,what they perceive. Another person would\Nsay well what is I depends on how I feel
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.52,0:21:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,feel and uh my thoughts.\NSo you can see your sense of I who you
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.55,0:21:43.20,Default,,0,0,0,,are your sense of reality your\Nidentification is constantly changing
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.20,0:21:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,and shifting. You're so used to it\Nchanging and shifting you don't even
Dialogue: 0,0:21:47.52,0:21:52.32,Default,,0,0,0,,notice it. One instant eye is what\Nyou're feeling. The next instant eye is
Dialogue: 0,0:21:52.32,0:21:56.15,Default,,0,0,0,,what you're thinking. The next instant\Neye is what it's imagining about the
Dialogue: 0,0:21:56.15,0:22:00.48,Default,,0,0,0,,future. The next instant eye is hanging\Nout redoing the past. So why did I do
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.48,0:22:07.03,Default,,0,0,0,,that? Uh\Nso the sense of I is constantly shifting
Dialogue: 0,0:22:07.03,0:22:12.24,Default,,0,0,0,,is diffuse and not really dependable.\NWhen you say I, what are you talking
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.24,0:22:20.40,Default,,0,0,0,,about? Uh what are you talking about? I\Nas a social personhood, I as a taxpayer.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:20.40,0:22:26.79,Default,,0,0,0,,I as an American.\NOkay. I as is feelings or thoughts.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:26.79,0:22:31.76,Default,,0,0,0,,Then finally you you get more\Nsophisticated and you say well I is
Dialogue: 0,0:22:31.76,0:22:38.96,Default,,0,0,0,,either all of them or none of them.\NTherefore the self is a blank screen
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.96,0:22:42.96,Default,,0,0,0,,upon which all the above can be\Nreflected.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:42.96,0:22:48.79,Default,,0,0,0,,You know whatever is on the TV set today\Nthat's what you are as your feelings and
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.79,0:22:54.64,Default,,0,0,0,,your thoughts today.\NSo the self becomes then the screen not
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.64,0:23:02.15,Default,,0,0,0,,the program on the TV set but the TV set\Nitself capable of any program.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:02.15,0:23:07.36,Default,,0,0,0,,So the self is therefore\Nnot just the content of what's going on
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.36,0:23:12.88,Default,,0,0,0,,with you but it's the whole context the\Nwhole phenomena within which the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:12.88,0:23:18.48,Default,,0,0,0,,subjective\Nuh appears and and returns.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:18.48,0:23:24.08,Default,,0,0,0,,rest internal versus rest external.\NDecart said there's this inner self, the
Dialogue: 0,0:23:24.08,0:23:28.88,Default,,0,0,0,,inner reality as you see it and then\Nthere's the external reality the way it
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.88,0:23:33.60,Default,,0,0,0,,is.\NThat's internal is your personal view of
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.60,0:23:38.88,Default,,0,0,0,,the world. I see the world thusly. I\Nbelieve thusly.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:38.88,0:23:44.96,Default,,0,0,0,,And then there's the world the way it is\Nwhich has nothing to do with you.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:44.96,0:23:49.67,Default,,0,0,0,,Nothing to do with you.\NSo when we use the arm to find out a
Dialogue: 0,0:23:49.67,0:23:55.12,Default,,0,0,0,,fact about something, we're trying to\Ntranscend
Dialogue: 0,0:23:55.12,0:24:00.96,Default,,0,0,0,,rest internally\Nand discover what is ex rest external.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.96,0:24:06.55,Default,,0,0,0,,What is the reality of the world itself?\NI know what I think about a certain
Dialogue: 0,0:24:06.55,0:24:12.72,Default,,0,0,0,,politician. I know how I feel about that\Npolitician. How much of that is real? So
Dialogue: 0,0:24:12.72,0:24:18.88,Default,,0,0,0,,then we ask the arm. We say so and so\Ncalibrates over 200 or not over 200 and
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.88,0:24:24.64,Default,,0,0,0,,we get then an objective read. So the\Npurpose of calibrating things is it
Dialogue: 0,0:24:24.64,0:24:29.84,Default,,0,0,0,,gives you a way of checking on your own\Nsense of reality and whether you're
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.84,0:24:34.88,Default,,0,0,0,,being deceived or not deceived.\NWhat happened to the wolf in sheep's
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.88,0:24:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,clothing? What was that one?\NWhat was it? What was that slide?
Dialogue: 0,0:24:42.00,0:24:47.20,Default,,0,0,0,,So the self knows\Nand the mind thinks
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.20,0:24:53.03,Default,,0,0,0,,that which is the self\Nis an automatic knowingness
Dialogue: 0,0:24:53.03,0:24:58.08,Default,,0,0,0,,about which you don't think. The mind is\Nseparate from the from that. The mind
Dialogue: 0,0:24:58.08,0:25:04.79,Default,,0,0,0,,thinks about things and the self just\Nknows them. I know there's a more to
Dialogue: 0,0:25:04.79,0:25:08.96,Default,,0,0,0,,this\Nto put my feet on
Dialogue: 0,0:25:08.96,0:25:15.67,Default,,0,0,0,,without thinking about it.\NI just know it's there because the self
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.67,0:25:20.40,Default,,0,0,0,,remembers all the things having to do\Nwith your security and in the back of
Dialogue: 0,0:25:20.40,0:25:25.52,Default,,0,0,0,,your mind warns you when you're getting\Ntoo close to the edge of the stage. Yes.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.52,0:25:31.60,Default,,0,0,0,,Okay.\NWe have to know the difference between
Dialogue: 0,0:25:31.60,0:25:37.91,Default,,0,0,0,,essence and appearance.\NUh essence and appearance.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.91,0:25:42.48,Default,,0,0,0,,What happened to our um what happened to\Nour wolf and sheep clothing? What what
Dialogue: 0,0:25:42.48,0:25:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,numbers what number slide is that?\N>> There we are.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.76,0:25:53.84,Default,,0,0,0,,All right. So, the difference to know\Nthe difference between
Dialogue: 0,0:25:53.84,0:25:59.36,Default,,0,0,0,,essence\Nhere's the essence here
Dialogue: 0,0:25:59.36,0:26:03.67,Default,,0,0,0,,and the sheep's clothing is the\Nappearance.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.67,0:26:08.40,Default,,0,0,0,,That's very helpful in understanding the\Npolitical world. If you don't understand
Dialogue: 0,0:26:08.40,0:26:14.24,Default,,0,0,0,,that, you can't understand why the the\Nphenomena that are happening are
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.24,0:26:24.79,Default,,0,0,0,,happening because inside of that sheep\Nwas actually the wolf paying them off.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:24.79,0:26:28.08,Default,,0,0,0,,If you want to get your way with them,\Nfigure out how do you pay them off
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.08,0:26:33.67,Default,,0,0,0,,apparently. Okay. I I got a kick out of\Nthe the news the last couple days. These
Dialogue: 0,0:26:33.67,0:26:37.03,Default,,0,0,0,,guys are supposed to be watching Bernie.\NWhat's his name? And they're all
Dialogue: 0,0:26:37.03,0:26:42.72,Default,,0,0,0,,watching pornography on their computers.\NI think it was hysterically funny.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.72,0:26:47.52,Default,,0,0,0,,The taxpayers are paying these guys to\Nwatch the investment and they're busy
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.52,0:26:52.08,Default,,0,0,0,,watching pornography on their computers.\NThat's hysterically funny. Isn't that
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.08,0:26:58.15,Default,,0,0,0,,funny?\NOkay, we'll move on then.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:58.15,0:27:03.03,Default,,0,0,0,,I think it's hysterically funny.\NCollapse of the banking system and the
Dialogue: 0,0:27:03.03,0:27:07.03,Default,,0,0,0,,investment firms, etc. because they're\Nall busy watching pornography. It's
Dialogue: 0,0:27:07.03,0:27:13.27,Default,,0,0,0,,hysterical.\NIt's like they don't get enough. You
Dialogue: 0,0:27:13.27,0:27:21.27,Default,,0,0,0,,know what?\NOkay.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:21.27,0:27:24.64,Default,,0,0,0,,Alice in Wonderland. We talk about\Nopinion,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.64,0:27:29.52,Default,,0,0,0,,the virtual reality of the media,\Nwatching the media. So, we're sub
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.52,0:27:33.36,Default,,0,0,0,,subject to something that people weren't\Nreally subject to that intensely when I
Dialogue: 0,0:27:33.36,0:27:37.44,Default,,0,0,0,,grew up.\NI mean, there was the daily newspaper
Dialogue: 0,0:27:37.44,0:27:43.36,Default,,0,0,0,,and there was the radio, but you weren't\Nbombarded with visual images. What
Dialogue: 0,0:27:43.36,0:27:46.96,Default,,0,0,0,,happens with visual images is that you\Nget programmed without realizing you've
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.96,0:27:52.15,Default,,0,0,0,,already been programmed. You think it's\Njust a picture, but that picture has
Dialogue: 0,0:27:52.15,0:27:56.32,Default,,0,0,0,,said the whole thing, come to a\Nconclusion, and already laid claim to
Dialogue: 0,0:27:56.32,0:28:01.60,Default,,0,0,0,,your vote. This picture is going to get\Nyou to vote for him. every in today's
Dialogue: 0,0:28:01.60,0:28:05.76,Default,,0,0,0,,world everybody there's protesters\Neverywhere. If you're not a protester
Dialogue: 0,0:28:05.76,0:28:09.76,Default,,0,0,0,,apparently you're nobody. You got to\Nfind something to protest about and then
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.76,0:28:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,you can get out with the field and where\Nyou can get arrested and punched.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:15.60,0:28:20.96,Default,,0,0,0,,You got to get out there and protest.\NUh otherwise you can't get punched in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:20.96,0:28:25.67,Default,,0,0,0,,the face and abused by the police and\Netc.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:25.67,0:28:30.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Uh, so you get to be a hero by going out\Nthere and express yourself. The old
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.79,0:28:35.20,Default,,0,0,0,,American way is to express yourself. I\Nhave no idea why everybody wants to
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.20,0:28:39.44,Default,,0,0,0,,express themsel.\NFrankly, I'm not interested in any of
Dialogue: 0,0:28:39.44,0:28:45.44,Default,,0,0,0,,their opinions.\NThere are 10,000 people out there
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.44,0:28:49.76,Default,,0,0,0,,demonstrating and protesting,\Nand I have the slightest interest in
Dialogue: 0,0:28:49.76,0:28:57.84,Default,,0,0,0,,what any of them think.\NWhy should I care what they think?
Dialogue: 0,0:28:57.84,0:29:00.64,Default,,0,0,0,,What they think is going to be gone\Ntomorrow. They'll be thinking about
Dialogue: 0,0:29:00.64,0:29:05.44,Default,,0,0,0,,something else. Because they love\Nprotest demonstrations.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.44,0:29:10.24,Default,,0,0,0,,People love protest demonstrations. We\Nthink they're all heroes out there. We
Dialogue: 0,0:29:10.24,0:29:14.72,Default,,0,0,0,,think all these protesters are out\Nthere. So, you know, such great
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.72,0:29:21.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Americans, American values, freedom,\Nfighting for American values.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.44,0:29:28.96,Default,,0,0,0,,Most protesters are out there for the\Negocentric fun of protesting. Resist.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:28.96,0:29:34.79,Default,,0,0,0,,Most pro protesters are out there for\Nthe egocentric fun of protesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:34.79,0:29:38.55,Default,,0,0,0,,Resist.\NAha.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:38.55,0:29:42.00,Default,,0,0,0,,So the next time you're going to allow\Nyour opinion to be swayed by the crowd
Dialogue: 0,0:29:42.00,0:29:45.20,Default,,0,0,0,,showing up at the something or other\Nconvention,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.20,0:29:50.24,Default,,0,0,0,,they're all out there because they get\Noff on it.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:50.24,0:29:55.44,Default,,0,0,0,,If you change what the what the protest\Nis about, same people go.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:55.44,0:29:59.91,Default,,0,0,0,,If you photograph protesters,\Nyou find the same group shows up all
Dialogue: 0,0:29:59.91,0:30:04.39,Default,,0,0,0,,over the place. They're protesting this\Nhere. They protest that there. The same
Dialogue: 0,0:30:04.39,0:30:08.32,Default,,0,0,0,,protesters show up because they're\Nhooked on protesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:08.32,0:30:11.60,Default,,0,0,0,,The excitement of the crowd. I mean,\Nwhat fun to get out there and holler and
Dialogue: 0,0:30:11.60,0:30:15.60,Default,,0,0,0,,hold up a sign. Down with then you put\Nanything in there. Down with whatever
Dialogue: 0,0:30:15.60,0:30:19.91,Default,,0,0,0,,you'll see today. Down with Republicans.\NDown with Democrats, down with virgins,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:19.91,0:30:25.44,Default,,0,0,0,,down with old people, down with social\Nsecurity, down with the government,
Dialogue: 0,0:30:25.44,0:30:31.36,Default,,0,0,0,,down with the president, down with the\NCongress, down with the
Dialogue: 0,0:30:31.36,0:30:35.44,Default,,0,0,0,,Everybody just gets off. They love\Nprotesting.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:35.44,0:30:41.52,Default,,0,0,0,,So they love to protest.\NThat's good to know it. So you're not
